\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Quince micro lite (v0.9)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
CyrusDreams
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
December 2025
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 10-cent-microcontroller,
 it was everywhere in the news.
 With a 32bit RISC-V core and useful peripherals,
 the CH32V003 from WCH is suited to many projects.
 But such a small microcontroller needs to be programmed via a dedicated adapter.
 In a forum at mikrocontroller.net,
 user F.P.
 analyzed the WCH LinkE debugging adapter and came to the conclusion that the binary code from WCH can be run on the USB enabled CH32V305 microcontroller.
 And because the CH32V305 da do so much more than its smaller sibling,
 the idea of this development board was born.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This description is valid for the 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

lite
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 variant of said development board an its first produced version 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

0.9
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Features of the Quince
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

micro
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

lite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
board dimensions of 21
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

mm * 51
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

mm are the same as a 
\emph on
RaspberryPi Pico
\emph default
,
 but it lacks the mounting holes,
 due to the use of an USB-C connector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the pinout of the board is designed to match the peripherals on the 
\emph on
ClockworkPi Pico Calc
\emph default
 mainboard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the boards has mounting pads for a microSD card slot and a connector for an OLED screen,
 if those are mounted,
 the board has the same features as a 
\emph on
Longan Nano
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the 
\emph on
LinkE
\emph default
 debug connector is found on the PCB edge,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 version omits the switchable target suply voltages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
on the bottom side of the PCB,
 a CAN bus transceiver can be mounted,
 this makes the Quince micro a small CAN bus node
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a RGB LED can be controlled from the microcontroller,
 two of the LEDs share the port with the Rx/Tx lines of the debug interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pinout of the Quince micro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename docmentation/quince_micro_pinout.png
	scale 50
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coloured signals match the ones on a 
\emph on
Raspberry Pi Pico
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remark:
 ports PB8 and PB9 will be exchanged in a later revision of the 
\emph on
Quince micro
\emph default
 to enable an additional I²C interface,
 compatible to the 
\emph on
Raspberry Pi
\emph default
 pinout.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quince micro compared to the Longan
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

nano
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename docmentation/quince_micro_longan_nano.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the bottom side of the 
\emph on
Quince micro
\emph default
,
 additional parts can be assembled to have a similar functionality as a 
\emph on
Longan nano
\emph default
 development board:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
microSD slot,
 the port pins are also available on pins 21,
 22,
 24 and 25 of the 
\emph on
Quince micro
\emph default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
eight-pin connector for OLED displays
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quince micro as a CAN bus node
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the bottom side of the PCB,
 a CAN bus transceiver can be mounted (position U50) with its decoupling caacitor (C51,
 100nF) and a four pole SMD pin header.
 With the available signals CAN-high,
 CAN-low,
 5V-supply and Ground,
 the Quince micro can be supplied with power and act as a CAN bus node.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename docmentation/quince-micro_CAN.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recommended are CAN-SIC transceivers (Signal Improvement Capability),
 if the additional cost of approximately 0.15€ is bearable for the intended project.
 These newer transceivers enable higher data rates and/or longer wiring distances than older CAN-FD transceivers.
 For 
\emph on
Quince micro
\emph default
,
 CAN transceivers with 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

standby
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 input and separate IO voltage are suitable.
 Examples of compatible transceivers are TJA1462 ,
 TCAN1462,
 TLE9371VSJ and others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quince micro is a Debugger
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Features of the Quince micro as a WCH LinkE Debugger
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the short side of the PCB,
 opposite of the USB-S connector,
 there are solder pads suitable for two sets of five pin headers.
 The pinout is close to the 
\emph on
WCH LinkE R0 1v3
\emph default
;
 the switchable supply pins are missing.
 Also not available is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ModeSelect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 button.
 Its functionality can be controlled via software,
 as stated in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

WCH-LinkUserManual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (version V2.4).
\end_layout

